# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ddr-memory-interface
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR SDRAM was first introduced in the late 1990s and is sometimes referred to as DDR1 to distinguish it from later generations.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] It has been succeeded by DDR2 SDRAM, DDR3 SDRAM, DDR4 SDRAM, and DDR5 SDRAM, each offering further improvements in speed, capacity, and efficiency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] These generations are not backward or forward compatible, meaning memory modules from different DDR versions cannot be used interchangeably on the same motherboard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR SDRAM typically transfers 64 bits of data at a time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Its effective transfer rate is calculated by multiplying the memory bus clock speed by two (for double data rate), then by the width of the data bus (64 bits), and dividing by eight to convert bits to bytes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] For example, a DDR module with a 100 MHz bus clock has a peak transfer rate of 1600 megabytes per second (MB/s).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] In the late 1980s IBM had built DRAMs using a dual-edge clocking feature and presented their results at the International Solid-State Circuits Convention in 1990.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] However, it was standard DRAM, not SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Samsung demonstrated the first DDR SDRAM memory prototype in 1997, and released the first commercial DDR SDRAM chip (64 Mbit) in June 1998, followed soon after by Hyundai Electronics (now SK Hynix) the same year.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The development of DDR began in 1996, before its specification was finalized by JEDEC in June 2000 (JESD79).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] JEDEC has set standards for the data rates of DDR SDRAM, divided into two parts.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The first specification is for memory chips, and the second is for memory modules.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The first retail PC motherboard using DDR SDRAM was released in August 2000.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] To increase memory capacity and bandwidth, chips are combined on a module.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] For instance, the 64-bit data bus for DIMM requires eight 8-bit chips, addressed in parallel.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Multiple chips with common address lines are called a memory rank.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The term was introduced to avoid confusion with chip internal **rows** and **banks**.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] A memory module may bear more than one rank.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The term **sides** would also be confusing because it incorrectly suggests the physical placement of chips on the module.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] All ranks are connected to the same memory bus (address + data).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The chip select signal is used to issue commands to specific rank.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Adding modules to the single memory bus creates additional electrical load on its drivers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] To mitigate the resulting bus signaling rate drop and overcome the memory bottleneck, new chipsets employ the multi-channel architecture.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Cycle time is the inverse of the I/O bus clock frequency; e.g., ⁠1/(100 MHz)⁠ = 10 ns per clock cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] There is no architectural difference between DDR SDRAM modules.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Modules are instead designed to run at different clock frequencies: for example, a PC-1600 module is designed to run at 100 MHz, and a PC-2100 is designed to run at 133 MHz.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] A module's clock speed designates the data rate at which it is guaranteed to perform, hence it is guaranteed to run at lower (underclocking) and can possibly run at higher (overclocking) clock rates than those for which it was made.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR SDRAM modules for desktop computers, dual in-line memory modules (DIMMs), have 184 pins (as opposed to 168 pins on SDRAM, or 240 pins on DDR2 SDRAM), and can be differentiated from SDRAM DIMMs by the number of notches (DDR SDRAM has one, SDRAM has two).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR SDRAM for notebook computers, SO-DIMMs, have 200 pins, which is the same number of pins as DDR2 SO-DIMMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] These two specifications are notched very similarly and care must be taken during insertion if unsure of a correct match.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Most DDR SDRAM operates at a voltage of 2.5 V, compared to 3.3 V for SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] This can significantly reduce power consumption.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Chips and modules with the DDR-400/PC-3200 standard have a nominal voltage of 2.6 V.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] 21–C defines three possible operating voltages for 184 pin DDR, as identified by the key notch position relative to its centerline.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Page 4.5.10-7 defines 2.5 V (left), 1.8 V (center), TBD (right), while page 4.20.5–40 nominates 3.3 V for the right notch position.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The orientation of the module for determining the key notch position is with 52 contact positions to the left and 40 contact positions to the right.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Increasing the operating voltage slightly can increase maximum speed but at the cost of higher power dissipation and heating, and at the risk of malfunctioning or damage.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Module and chip characteristics are inherently linked.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Total module capacity is a product of one chip's capacity and the number of chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] ECC modules multiply it by 8⁄9 because they use 1 bit per byte (8 bits) for error correction.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] A module of any particular size can therefore be assembled either from 32 small chips (36 for ECC memory), or 16(18) or 8(9) bigger ones.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR memory bus width per channel is 64 bits (72 for ECC memory).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Total module bit width is a product of bits per chip and number of chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] It also equals number of ranks (rows) multiplied by DDR memory bus width.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Consequently, a module with a greater number of chips or using ×8 chips instead of ×4 will have more ranks.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] GB modules are used, they most likely will not work.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] only for registered modules designed specifically for servers, but some generic manufacturers do not comply.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] chips are mainly used in desktops/notebooks but are making an entry into the server market.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] There are normally 4 banks and only one row can be active in each bank.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] From Ballot JCB-99-70, and modified by numerous other Board Ballots, formulated under the cognizance of Committee JC-42.3 on DRAM Parametrics.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] "This comprehensive standard defines all required aspects of 64Mb through 1Gb DDR SDRAMs with X4/X8/X16 data interfaces, including features, functionality, ac and dc parametrics, packages and pin assignments.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] PC3200 is DDR SDRAM designed to operate at 200 MHz using DDR-400 chips with a bandwidth of 3,200 MB/s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Because PC3200 memory transfers data on both the rising and falling clock edges, its effective clock rate is 400 MHz.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] 1 GB PC3200 non-ECC modules are usually made with 16 512 Mbit chips, 8 on each side (512 Mbits × 16 chips) / (8 bits (per byte)) = 1,024 MB.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The individual chips making up a 1 GB memory module are usually organized as 226 8-bit words, commonly expressed as 64M×8.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Memory manufactured in this way is low-density RAM and is usually compatible with any motherboard specifying PC3200 DDR-400 memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR (DDR1) was superseded by DDR2 SDRAM, which had modifications for a higher clock frequency and again doubled throughput, but operates on the same principle as DDR.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Competing with DDR2 was Rambus XDR DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR2 dominated due to cost and support factors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR2 was in turn superseded by DDR3 SDRAM, which offered higher performance for increased bus speeds and new features.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR3 has been superseded by DDR4 SDRAM, which was first produced in 2011 and whose standards were still in flux (2012) with significant architectural changes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR's prefetch buffer depth is 2 (bits), while DDR2 uses 4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Although the effective clock rates of DDR2 are higher than DDR, the overall performance was not greater in the early implementations, primarily due to the high latencies of the first DDR2 modules.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR2 started to be effective by the end of 2004, as modules with lower latencies became available.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Memory manufacturers stated that it was impractical to mass produce DDR1 memory with effective transfer rates in excess of 400 MHz (i.e.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] 400 MT/s and 200 MHz external clock) due to internal speed limitations.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR2 picks up where DDR1 leaves off, utilizing internal clock rates similar to DDR1, but is available at effective transfer rates of 400 MHz and higher.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR3 advances extended the ability to preserve internal clock rates while providing higher effective transfer rates by again doubling the prefetch depth.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The DDR4 SDRAM is a high-speed dynamic random-access memory internally configured as 16 banks, 4 bank groups with 4 banks for each bank group for ×4/×8 and 8 banks, 2 bank groups with 4 banks for each bank group for ×16 DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The DDR4 SDRAM uses an 8*n* prefetch architecture to achieve high-speed operation.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] The 8*n* prefetch architecture is combined with an interface designed to transfer two data words per clock cycle at the I/O pins.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] A single read or write operation for the DDR4 SDRAM consists of a single 8*n*-bit-wide 4-clock data transfer at the internal DRAM core and 8 corresponding *n*-bit-wide half-clock-cycle data transfers at the I/O pins.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] RDRAM was a particularly expensive alternative to DDR SDRAM, and most manufacturers dropped its support from their chipsets.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] DDR1 memory's prices substantially increased from Q2 2008, while DDR2 prices declined.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] In January 2009, 1 GB DDR1 was 2–3 times more expensive than 1 GB DDR2.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] LPDDR is an acronym that some enterprises use for LPDDR SDRAM, a type of memory used in some portable electronic devices, like mobile phones, handhelds, and digital audio players.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr-sdram] Through techniques including reduced voltage supply and advanced refresh options, LPDDR can achieve greater power efficiency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Released to the market in 2014, it is a variant of dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), some of which have been in use since the early 1970s, and a higher-speed successor to the DDR2 and DDR3 technologies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4 is not compatible with any earlier type of random-access memory (RAM) due to different signaling voltage and physical interface, besides other factors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4 SDRAM was released to the public market in Q2 2014, focusing on ECC memory, while the non-ECC DDR4 modules became available in Q3 2014, accompanying the launch of Haswell-E processors that require DDR4 memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The primary advantages of DDR4 over its predecessor, DDR3, include higher module density and lower voltage requirements, coupled with higher data rate transfer speeds.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The DDR4 standard allows for DIMMs of up to 64 GB in capacity, compared to DDR3's maximum of 16 GB per DIMM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Unlike previous generations of DDR memory, prefetch has *not* been increased above the 8n used in DDR3; the basic burst size is eight 64-bit words, and higher bandwidths are achieved by sending more read/write commands per second.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] To allow this, the standard divides the DRAM banks into two or four selectable bank groups, where transfers to different bank groups may be done more rapidly.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Because power consumption increases with speed, the reduced voltage allows higher speed operation without unreasonable power and cooling requirements.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In April 2013, a news writer at International Data Group (IDG) – an American technology research business originally part of IDC – produced an analysis of their perceptions related to DDR4 SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The conclusions were that the increasing popularity of mobile computing and other devices using slower but low-powered memory, the slowing of growth in the traditional desktop computing sector, and the consolidation of the memory manufacturing marketplace, meant that margins on RAM were tight.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] As a result, the desired premium pricing for the new technology was harder to achieve, and capacity had shifted to other sectors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] SDRAM manufacturers and chipset creators were, to an extent, "stuck between a rock and a hard place" where "nobody wants to pay a premium for DDR4 products, and manufacturers don't want to make the memory if they are not going to get a premium", according to Mike Howard from iSuppli.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] A switch in consumer sentiment toward desktop computing and release of processors having DDR4 support by Intel and AMD could therefore potentially lead to "aggressive" growth.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Intel's 2014 Haswell roadmap, revealed the company's first use of DDR4 SDRAM in Haswell-EP processors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] AMD's Ryzen processors, revealed in 2016 and shipped in 2017, use DDR4 SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Internal banks are increased to 16 (4 bank select bits), with up to 8 ranks per DIMM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Increased memory density is anticipated, possibly using TSV ("through-silicon via") or other 3D stacking processes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The DDR4 specification will include standardized 3D stacking "from the start" according to JEDEC, with provision for up to 8 stacked dies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] X-bit Labs predicted that "as a result DDR4 memory chips with very high density will become relatively inexpensive".
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Switched memory banks are also an anticipated option for servers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In 2008, the book *Wafer Level 3-D ICs Process Technology* highlighted concerns about the increasing die area consumption due to non-scaling analog elements like charge pumps, voltage regulators, and additional circuitry.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Consequently, the proportion of die allocated to the memory array itself has decreased over time: from **70–78%** for SDRAM and DDR1 to **47%** for DDR2, **38%** for DDR3, and potentially less than **30%** for DDR4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The specification defined standards for ×4, ×8 and ×16 memory devices with capacities of 2, 4, 8 and 16 Gbit.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Although it still operates in fundamentally the same way, DDR4 makes one major change to the command formats used by previous SDRAM generations.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] A new command signal, ACT, is low to indicate the activate (open row) command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The activate command requires more address bits than any other (18 row address bits in a 16 Gbit part), so the standard RAS, CAS, and WE active low signals are shared with high-order address bits that are not used when ACT is high.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The combination of RAS=L and CAS=WE=H that previously encoded an activate command is unused.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] As in previous SDRAM encodings, A10 is used to select command variants: auto-precharge on read and write commands, and one bank vs. all banks for the precharge command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] It also selects two variants of the ZQ calibration command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] As in DDR3, A12 is used to request *burst chop*: truncation of an 8-transfer burst after four transfers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Although the bank is still busy and unavailable for other commands until eight transfer times have elapsed, a different bank can be accessed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Also, the number of bank addresses has been increased greatly.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] There are four bank select bits to select up to 16 banks within each DRAM: two bank address bits (BA0, BA1), and two bank group bits (BG0, BG1).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] There are additional timing restrictions when accessing banks within the same bank group; it is faster to access a bank in a different bank group.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In addition, there are three chip select signals (C0, C1, C2), allowing up to eight stacked chips to be placed inside a single DRAM package.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] These effectively act as three more bank select bits, bringing the total to seven (128 possible banks).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Rowhammer mitigation techniques include larger storage capacitors, modifying the address lines to use address space layout randomization and dual-voltage I/O lines that further isolate potential boundary conditions that might result in instability at high write/read speeds.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4 memory is supplied in 288-pin dual in-line memory modules (DIMMs), similar in size to 240-pin DDR3 DIMMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] **DDR4 RAM** modules feature pins that are spaced more closely at **0.85 mm** compared to the **1.0 mm** spacing in DDR3, allowing for a higher pin density within the same standard DIMM length of **133.35 mm** (5¼ inches).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The height of DDR4 modules is slightly increased to **31.25 mm** (1.23 inches) from **30.35 mm** (1.2 inches) to facilitate easier signal routing.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Additionally, the thickness of DDR4 modules has been increased to **1.2 mm** from **1.0 mm** to support more signal layers, enhancing overall performance and reliability.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4 DIMM modules have a slightly curved edge connector so not all of the pins are engaged at the same time during module insertion, lowering the insertion force.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4 SO-DIMMs have 260 pins instead of the 204 pins of DDR3 SO-DIMMs, spaced at 0.5 rather than 0.6 mm, and are 2.0 mm wider (69.6 versus 67.6 mm), but remain the same 30 mm in height.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] For its Skylake microarchitecture, Intel designed a SO-DIMM package named UniDIMM, which can be populated with either DDR3 or DDR4 chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] At the same time, the integrated memory controller (IMC) of Skylake CPUs is announced to be capable of working with either type of memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The purpose of UniDIMMs is to help in the market transition from DDR3 to DDR4, where pricing and availability may make it undesirable to switch the RAM type.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] UniDIMMs have the same dimensions and number of pins as regular DDR4 SO-DIMMs, but the edge connector's notch is placed differently to avoid accidental use in incompatible DDR4 SO-DIMM sockets.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] DDR4-xxxx denotes per-bit data transfer rate, and is normally used to describe DDR chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] PC4-xxxxx denotes overall transfer rate, in megabytes per second, and applies only to modules (assembled DIMMs).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Because DDR4 memory modules transfer data on a bus that is 8 bytes (64 data bits) wide, module peak transfer rate is calculated by taking transfers per second and multiplying by eight.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] At the 2016 Intel Developer Forum, the future of DDR5 SDRAM was discussed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] The specifications were finalized at the end of 2016 – but no modules would be available until 2020.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Other memory technologies – namely HBM in version 3 and 4 – aiming to replace DDR4 have also been proposed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In 2011, JEDEC introduced the **Wide I/O 2** standard, which features stacked memory dies placed directly on top of the CPU within the same package.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] This configuration provides higher bandwidth and improved power efficiency compared to DDR4 SDRAM, thanks to its wide interface and short signal lengths.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Wide I/O 2 aims to replace various mobile DDRX SDRAM standards used in high-performance embedded and mobile devices like smartphones.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In parallel, Hynix developed **High Bandwidth Memory (HBM)**, standardized as JEDEC JESD235.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Both Wide I/O 2 and HBM utilize a very wide parallel memory interface—up to 512 bits for Wide I/O 2 compared to 64 bits for DDR4—although they operate at lower frequencies than DDR4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Wide I/O 2 is designed for high-performance, compact devices, often integrated into processors or system on a chip (SoC) packages.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In contrast, HBM targets graphics memory and general computing, while **Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC)** is aimed at high-end servers and enterprise applications.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Micron Technology's Hybrid Memory Cube (HMC) stacked memory uses a serial interface.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] Many other computer buses have migrated towards replacing parallel buses with serial buses, for example by the evolution of Serial ATA replacing Parallel ATA, PCI Express replacing PCI, and serial ports replacing parallel ports.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In general, serial buses are easier to scale up and have fewer wires/traces, making circuit boards using them easier to design.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] In the longer term, experts speculate that non-volatile RAM types like PCM (phase-change memory), RRAM (resistive random-access memory), or MRAM (magnetoresistive random-access memory) could replace DDR4 SDRAM and its successors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr4-sdram] GDDR5 SGRAM is a graphics type of DDR3 synchronous graphics RAM, which was introduced before DDR4, and is not a successor to DDR4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] A new feature called Decision Feedback Equalization (DFE) enables input/output (I/O) speed scalability for higher bandwidth and performance improvement.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 has about the same 14 ns latency as DDR4 and DDR3.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 octuples the maximum dual in-line memory module (DIMM) capacity from 64 GB to 512 GB.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 also has higher frequencies than DDR4, up to 9.6 GT/s is currently possible, 8.2 GT/s translates into around 64 GB/s of bandwidth.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Speeds of more than 13 GT/s have been achieved using liquid nitrogen cooling.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Rambus announced a working DDR5 DIMM in September 2017.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] On November 15, 2018, SK Hynix announced completion of its first DDR5 RAM chip; running at 5.2 GT/s at 1.1 V.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] In February 2019, SK Hynix announced a 6.4 GT/s chip, the highest speed specified by the preliminary DDR5 standard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The first production DDR5 DRAM chip was officially launched by SK Hynix on October 6, 2020.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The separate JEDEC standard Low Power Double Data Rate 5 (LPDDR5), intended for laptops and smartphones, was released in February 2019.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Compared to DDR4, DDR5 further reduces memory voltage to 1.1 V, a reduction from the 1.2 V required by DDR4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 modules incorporate on-board voltage regulators in order to reach higher speeds.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] In 2024 the first CUDIMM (clocked unbuffered DIMM) and CSODIMM (clocked SODIMM) modules were introduced together with Intel Arrow Lake.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] These modules include a component to re-drive the clock signal to help reach higher speeds.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] AMD does not support CUDIMM, though Zen 5 will accept CUDIMMs in bypass mode.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] In 2026 ASRock and Intel released the DDR5 HUDIMM (half unbuffered DIMM) modules, it populating one 32-bit subchannel per DIMM, designed for budget but reduced-performance computer markets.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] It requires the UEFI/BIOS to support HUDIMM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Unlike DDR4, all DDR5 chips have on-die error-correction code, that detects and corrects storage errors before forwarding data to the CPU, to improve reliability and allow denser RAM chips with higher per-chip defect rate to be used.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] On-die ECC happens at a lower level than true ECC memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] It does not have extra chips and data lines to the CPU and does not report any details about whether errors are detected, unlike externally-controlled ECC.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Sophisticated algorithms have been built to infer the existence of corrected errors based on non-corrected errors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Each DDR5 DIMM has two independent subchannels.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Earlier DIMM generations featured only a single channel and one CA (Command/Address) bus controlling the whole memory module with its 64 (for non-ECC) or 72 (for ECC) data lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Both subchannels on a DDR5 DIMM each have their own CA bus, controlling 32 bits for non-ECC memory and either 36 or 40 data lines for ECC memory, resulting in a total number of either 64, 72 or 80 data lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The reduced bus width is compensated by a doubled minimum burst length of 16, which preserves the minimum access size of 64 bytes, which matches the cache line size used by modern x86 microprocessors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 also decreased the refresh interval from 64 ms to 32 ms when operating up to 85°C.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] At 85°C to 95°C refresh times are 16 ms.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The tRFC4 mechanism from DDR4 is retired.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] It also provides two refresh commands: REFab and REFsb.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Multiple DDR5 memory chips can be mounted on a circuit board to form memory modules.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] For use in personal computers and servers, DDR5 memory is usually supplied in 288-pin dual in-line memory modules, more commonly known as DIMMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] As with previous memory generations, there are multiple DIMM variants available for DDR5.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Unbuffered memory modules (UDIMMs) directly expose the memory chip interface to the module connector.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Registered or load-reduced variants (RDIMMs/LRDIMMs) use additional active circuitry on the memory module in order to buffer the signals between the memory controller and the DRAM chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] This reduces the capacitive load on the DDR5 bus.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 UDIMMs use 5 V input, whereas RDIMMs and LRDIMMs use 12 V.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] In order to prevent damage by accidental insertion of the wrong memory type, DDR5 UDIMMs and (L)RDIMMs are not mechanically compatible.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Additionally, DDR5 DIMMs are supplied with management interface power at 3.3 V, and use on-board circuitry (a power management integrated circuit and associated passive components) to convert to the lower voltage required by the memory chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Final voltage regulation close to the point of use provides more stable power, and mirrors the development of voltage regulator modules for CPU power supplies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Standard DDR5 memory speeds range from 4,000 to 6,400 million transfers per second (PC5-32000 to PC5-51200).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Higher speeds may be added later, as happened with previous generations.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] XMP profiles currently allow 8000 MT/s with 1.400 V/1.450 V, which is much higher than 1.1 V in the JEDEC standard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Compared to DDR4 SDRAM, the minimum burst length was doubled to 16, with the option of "burst chop" after eight transfers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The command encoding was significantly rearranged, eliminating the traditional RAS and CAS signals in favour of an system resembling LPDDR4: commands are sent using either one or two cycles with a 14-bit bus.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Some simple commands (e.g. precharge) take one cycle, while any that include an address (activate, read, write) use two cycles to include 28 bits of information.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Also like LPDDR, there are now 256 8-bit mode registers, rather than eight 13-bit mode registers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Also, rather than one register (MR7) being reserved for use by the registered clock driver chip, a complete second bank of mode registers is defined (selected using the CW bit).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The new "Write pattern" command is similar to a normal write command, but instead of taking data from the bus, the range is filled in with copies of a one-byte mode register (which defaults to all-zero) instead of individual data.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] While this takes just as long to complete as a normal write, it frees up the data bus for operations on other banks.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The new "Precharge same bank" command precharges a given bank number in all bank groups.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The "Multi-purpose command" includes various sub-commands for training and calibration of the data bus.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The "Burst length" control bit normally requests "burst chop" mode, which transfers only 8 words (although the bank remains busy for 16 word times), but can instead be configured via a mode register to instead request a double-sized 32-word burst.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] The 12th generation Alder Lake, 13th generation Raptor Lake, as well as 14th generation Raptor Lake Refresh CPUs support both DDR5 and DDR4 but, usually, there are only DIMM sockets for either one or the other on a motherboard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Some mainboards with Intel's H610 chipset support both DDR4 and DDR5, but not simultaneously.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Sapphire Rapids server CPUs, Core Ultra Series 1 Meteor Lake mobile CPUs, and the latest Core Ultra Series 2 Arrow Lake desktop CPUs all exclusively support DDR5 and Arrow Lake also supports CUDIMM DDR5 memory standard that allows for higher default speed of 6400 MT/s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] DDR5 and LPDDR5 are supported by the Ryzen 6000 series mobile APUs, powered by their Zen 3+ architecture.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Ryzen 7000 and Ryzen 9000 series desktop processors also support DDR5 memory as standard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/ddr5-sdram] Epyc fourth-generation *Genoa* and *Bergamo* server CPUs have support for 12-channel DDR5 on the SP5 socket.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] In computing, **double data rate** (**DDR**) describes a computer bus that transfers data on both the rising and falling edges of the clock signal and hence doubles the memory bandwidth by transferring data twice per clock cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] This is also known as **double pumped**, **dual-pumped**, and **double transition**.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] The term **toggle mode** is used in the context of NAND flash memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] The simplest way to design a clocked electronic circuit is to make it perform one transfer per full cycle (rise and fall) of a clock signal.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] This, however, requires that the clock signal changes twice per transfer, while the data lines change at most once per transfer.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] When operating at a high bandwidth, signal integrity limitations constrain the clock frequency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] By using both edges of the clock, the data signals operate with the same limiting frequency, thereby doubling the data transmission rate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] This technique has been used for microprocessor front-side busses, Ultra-3 SCSI, expansion buses (AGP, PCI-X), graphics memory (GDDR), main memory (both RDRAM and DDR1 through DDR5), and the HyperTransport bus on AMD's Athlon 64 processors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] It is more recently being used for other systems with high data transfer speed requirements – as an example, for the output of analog-to-digital converters (ADCs).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] DDR should not be confused with dual channel, in which each memory channel accesses two RAM modules simultaneously.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] The two technologies are independent of each other and many motherboards use both, by using DDR memory in a dual channel configuration.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] An alternative to double or quad pumping is to use self-clocking signals.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] This tactic was chosen by InfiniBand and PCI Express.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Describing the bandwidth of a double-pumped bus can be confusing.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Each clock edge is referred to as a *beat*, with two beats (one upbeat and one downbeat) per cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Technically, the hertz is a unit of *cycles* per second, but many people refer to the number of *transfers* per second.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Careful usage generally talks about "500 MHz, double data rate" or "1000 MT/s", but many refer casually to a "1000 MHz bus," even though no signal cycles faster than 500 MHz.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Using the letter "T" for transfers is technically incorrect, as T is assigned by the International System of Units to the Tesla, a unit of magnetic flux density, so "MT/s" is a rate of change of magnetic field strength.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] However, given that such rapid magnetic field changes are confined to the specialized field of kicker magnet design, and such a magnet might switch a 0.03 T field in 0.3 μs, a rate of 0.1 T/μs = 0.1 MT/s, the ambiguity is not a problem in practice.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] DDR SDRAM popularized the technique of referring to the bus bandwidth in megabytes per second, the product of the transfer rate and the bus width in bytes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] DDR SDRAM operating with a 100 MHz clock is called DDR-200 (after its 200 MT/s data transfer rate), and a 64-bit (8-byte) wide DIMM operated at that data rate is called PC-1600, after its 1600 MB/s peak (theoretical) bandwidth.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] DDR SDRAM uses double-data-rate signaling only on the data lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Address and control signals are still sent to the DRAM once per clock *cycle* (to be precise, on the rising edge of the clock), and timing parameters such as CAS latency are specified in clock cycles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] Some less common DRAM interfaces, notably LPDDR2, GDDR5 and XDR DRAM, also send commands and addresses using double data rate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/double-data-rate] DDR5 uses two 7-bit double data rate command/address buses to each DIMM, where a registered clock driver chip converts to a 14-bit SDR bus to each memory chip.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While most DRAM memory cell designs use a capacitor and transistor, some only use two transistors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the designs where a capacitor is used, the capacitor can either be charged or discharged; these two states are taken to represent the two values of a bit, conventionally called 0 and 1.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The electric charge on the capacitors gradually leaks away; without intervention, the data on the capacitor would soon be lost.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To prevent this, DRAM requires an external memory refresh circuit which periodically rewrites the data in the capacitors, restoring them to their original charge.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This refresh process is the defining characteristic of dynamic random-access memory, in contrast to static random-access memory (SRAM) which does not require data to be refreshed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Unlike flash memory, DRAM is volatile memory (as opposed to non-volatile memory), since it loses its data quickly when power is removed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, DRAM does exhibit limited data remanence.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM typically takes the form of an integrated circuit chip, which can consist of dozens to billions of DRAM memory cells.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM chips are widely used in digital electronics where low-cost, high-capacity computer memory is required.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] One of the largest applications for DRAM is the *main memory* (colloquially called the RAM) in modern computers and graphics cards (where the main memory is called the *graphics memory*).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] It is also used in many portable devices and video game consoles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In contrast, SRAM, which is faster and more expensive than DRAM, is typically used where speed is of greater concern than cost and size, such as the cache memories in processors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The need to refresh DRAM demands more complicated circuitry and timing than SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This complexity is offset by the structural simplicity of DRAM memory cells: only one transistor and a capacitor are required per bit, compared to four or six transistors in SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This allows DRAM to reach very high densities with a simultaneous reduction in cost per bit.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Refreshing the data consumes power, causing a variety of techniques to be used to manage the overall power consumption.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For this reason, DRAM usually needs to operate with a memory controller; the memory controller needs to know DRAM parameters, especially memory timings, to initialize DRAMs, which may be different depending on different DRAM manufacturers and part numbers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM had a 47% increase in the price-per-bit in 2017, the largest jump in 30 years since the 45% jump in 1988.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 2018, a "key characteristic of the DRAM market is that there are currently only three major suppliers — Micron Technology, SK Hynix and Samsung Electronics" that are "keeping a pretty tight rein on their capacity".
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM (DDR4, DDR, and flash memory/NAND) price has in early 2026 "experienced compounded increases, some exceeding 200%, since early 2025 .. [because of] unprecedented demand coming from the AI sector ..
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] HBM is crowding out commodity DRAM capacity.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Other manufacturers make and sell DIMMs but not the DRAM chips in them, such as Kingston Technology, and some manufacturers sell stacked DRAM (used e.g. in the fastest supercomputers on the exascale) separately such as Viking Technology.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Others sell such integrated into other products, such as Fujitsu into its CPUs, AMD in GPUs, and Nvidia, with HBM2 in some of their GPU chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The cryptanalytic machine code-named *Aquarius* used at Bletchley Park during World War II incorporated a hard-wired dynamic memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Paper tape was read and the characters on it "were remembered in a dynamic store".
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The store used a large bank of capacitors, which were either charged or not, a charged capacitor representing cross (1) and an uncharged capacitor dot (0).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the charge gradually leaked away, a periodic pulse was applied to top up those still charged (hence the term 'dynamic')".
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In November 1965, Toshiba introduced a bipolar dynamic RAM for its electronic calculator Toscal BC-1411.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 1966, Tomohisa Yoshimaru and Hiroshi Komikawa from Toshiba applied for a Japanese patent of a memory circuit composed of several transistors and a capacitor, in 1967 they applied for a patent in the US.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The earliest forms of DRAM mentioned above used bipolar transistors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While it offered improved performance over magnetic-core memory, bipolar DRAM could not compete with the lower price of the then-dominant magnetic-core memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Capacitors had also been used for earlier memory schemes, such as the drum of the Atanasoff–Berry Computer, the Williams tube and the Selectron tube.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Robert Dennard invented modern DRAM architecture in which there's a single MOS transistor per capacitor, at the IBM Thomas J.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Watson Research Center, while he was working on MOS memory and was trying to create an alternative to SRAM which required six MOS transistors for each bit of data.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While examining the characteristics of MOS technology, he found it was capable of building capacitors, and that storing a charge or no charge on the MOS capacitor could represent the 1 and 0 of a bit, while the MOS transistor could control writing the charge to the capacitor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This led to his development of the single-transistor MOS DRAM memory cell.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] He filed a patent in 1967, and was granted U.S. patent number 3,387,286 in 1968.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS memory offered higher performance, was cheaper, and consumed less power, than magnetic-core memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS DRAM chips were commercialized in 1969 by Advanced Memory Systems, Inc., of Sunnyvale, CA.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This 1024 bit chip was sold to Honeywell, Raytheon, Wang Laboratories, and others.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The same year, Honeywell asked Intel to make a DRAM using a three-transistor cell that they had developed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This became the Intel 1102 in early 1970.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, the 1102 had many problems, prompting Intel to begin work on their own improved design, in secrecy to avoid conflict with Honeywell.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This became the first commercially available DRAM, the Intel 1103, in October 1970, despite initial problems with low yield until the fifth revision of the masks.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The 1103 was designed by Joel Karp and laid out by Pat Earhart.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The masks were cut by Barbara Maness and Judy Garcia.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] MOS memory overtook magnetic-core memory as the dominant memory technology in the early 1970s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first DRAM with multiplexed row and column address lines was the Mostek MK4096 4 Kbit DRAM designed by Robert Proebsting and introduced in 1973.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This addressing scheme uses the same address pins to receive the low half and the high half of the address of the memory cell being referenced, switching between the two halves on alternating bus cycles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was a radical advance, effectively halving the number of address lines required, which enabled it to fit into packages with fewer pins, a cost advantage that grew with every jump in memory size.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The MK4096 proved to be a very robust design for customer applications.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] At the 16 Kbit density, the cost advantage increased; the 16 Kbit Mostek MK4116 DRAM, introduced in 1976, achieved greater than 75% worldwide DRAM market share.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, as density increased to 64 Kbit in the early 1980s, Mostek and other US manufacturers were overtaken by Japanese DRAM manufacturers, which dominated the US and worldwide markets during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Early in 1985, Gordon Moore decided to withdraw Intel from producing DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] By 1986, many, but not all, United States chip makers had stopped making DRAMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Micron Technology and Texas Instruments continued to produce them commercially, and IBM produced them for internal use.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Prices for the 64K product plummeted to as low as 35 cents apiece from $3.50 within 18 months, with disastrous financial consequences for some U.S. firms.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] On 4 December 1985 the US Commerce Department's International Trade Administration ruled in favor of the complaint.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Synchronous dynamic random-access memory (SDRAM) was developed by Samsung.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first commercial SDRAM chip was the Samsung KM48SL2000, which had a capacity of 16 Mbit, and was introduced in 1992.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first commercial DDR SDRAM (double data rate SDRAM) memory chip was Samsung's 64 Mbit DDR SDRAM chip, released in 1998.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Later, in 2001, Japanese DRAM makers accused Korean DRAM manufacturers of dumping.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 2002, the United States Department of Justice began an investigation which ultimately found several computer manufacturers guilty of DRAM price fixing.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM is usually arranged in a rectangular array of charge storage cells consisting of one capacitor and transistor per data bit.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The figure to the right shows a simple example with a four-by-four cell matrix.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some DRAM matrices are many thousands of cells in height and width.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The long horizontal lines connecting each row are known as word-lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Each column of cells is composed of two bit-lines, each connected to every other storage cell in the column (the illustration to the right does not include this important detail).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] They are generally known as the *+* and *−* bit lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A sense amplifier is essentially a pair of cross-connected inverters between the bit-lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first inverter is connected with input from the + bit-line and output to the − bit-line.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The second inverter's input is from the − bit-line with output to the + bit-line.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This results in positive feedback which stabilizes after one bit-line is fully at its highest voltage and the other bit-line is at the lowest possible voltage.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bit-lines are precharged to exactly equal voltages that are in between high and low logic levels (e.g., 0.5 V if the two levels are 0 and 1 V).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bit-lines are physically symmetrical to keep the capacitance equal, and therefore at this time their voltages are equal.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Because the bit-lines are relatively long, they have enough capacitance to maintain the precharged voltage for a brief time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The desired row's word-line is then driven high to connect a cell's storage capacitor to its bit-line.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This causes the transistor to conduct, transferring charge from the storage cell to the connected bit-line (if the stored value is 1) or from the connected bit-line to the storage cell (if the stored value is 0).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As the other bit-line holds 0.50 V there is a small voltage difference between the two twisted bit-lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifiers are now connected to the bit-lines pairs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Positive feedback then occurs from the cross-connected inverters, thereby amplifying the small voltage difference between the odd and even row bit-lines of a particular column until one bit line is fully at the lowest voltage and the other is at the maximum high voltage.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Once this has happened, the row is *open* (the desired cell data is available).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] All storage cells in the open row are sensed simultaneously, and the sense amplifier outputs latched.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A column address then selects which latch bit to connect to the external data bus.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Reads of different columns in the same row can be performed without a row opening delay because, for the open row, all data has already been sensed and latched.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] While reading of columns in an open row is occurring, current is flowing back up the bit-lines from the output of the sense amplifiers and recharging the storage cells.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This reinforces (i.e. refreshes) the charge in the storage cell by increasing the voltage in the storage capacitor if it was charged to begin with, or by keeping it discharged if it was empty.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Note that due to the length of the bit-lines there is a fairly long propagation delay for the charge to be transferred back to the cell's capacitor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This takes significant time past the end of sense amplification, and thus overlaps with one or more column reads.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When done with reading all the columns in the current open row, the word-line is switched off to disconnect the storage cell capacitors (the row is closed) from the bit-lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifier is switched off, and the bit-lines are precharged again.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To store data, a row is opened and a given column's sense amplifier is temporarily forced to the desired high or low-voltage state, thus causing the bit-line to charge or discharge the cell storage capacitor to the desired value.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Due to the sense amplifier's positive feedback configuration, it will hold a bit-line at stable voltage even after the forcing voltage is removed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] During a write to a particular cell, all the columns in a row are sensed simultaneously just as during reading, so although only a single column's storage-cell capacitor charge is changed, the entire row is refreshed (written back in), as illustrated in the figure to the right.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Typically, manufacturers specify that each row must be refreshed every 64 ms or less, as defined by the JEDEC standard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some systems refresh every row in a burst of activity involving all rows every 64 ms.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Other systems refresh one row at a time staggered throughout the 64 ms interval.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For example, a system with 213 = 8,192 rows would require a staggered refresh rate of one row every 7.8 μs which is 64 ms divided by 8,192 rows.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A few real-time systems refresh a portion of memory at a time determined by an external timer function that governs the operation of the rest of a system, such as the vertical blanking interval that occurs every 10–20 ms in video equipment.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The row address of the row that will be refreshed next is maintained by external logic or a counter within the DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A system that provides the row address (and the refresh command) does so to have greater control over when to refresh and which row to refresh.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is done to minimize conflicts with memory accesses, since such a system has both knowledge of the memory access patterns and the refresh requirements of the DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When the row address is supplied by a counter within the DRAM, the system relinquishes control over which row is refreshed and only provides the refresh command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Some modern DRAMs are capable of self-refresh; no external logic is required to instruct the DRAM to refresh or to provide a row address.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Under some conditions, most of the data in DRAM can be recovered even if the DRAM has not been refreshed for several minutes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Many parameters are required to fully describe the timing of DRAM operation.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Thus, the generally quoted number is the /RAS low to valid data out time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is the time to open a row, settle the sense amplifiers, and deliver the selected column data to the output.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is also the minimum /RAS low time, which includes the time for the amplified data to be delivered back to recharge the cells.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The time to read additional bits from an open page is much less, defined by the /CAS to /CAS cycle time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The quoted number is the clearest way to compare between the performance of different DRAM memories, as it sets the slower limit regardless of the row length or page size.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Bigger arrays forcibly result in larger bit line capacitance and longer propagation delays, which cause this time to increase as the sense amplifier settling time is dependent on both the capacitance as well as the propagation latency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This is countered in modern DRAM chips by instead integrating many more complete DRAM arrays within a single chip, to accommodate more capacity without becoming too slow.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When such a RAM is accessed by clocked logic, the times are generally rounded up to the nearest clock cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For example, when accessed by a 100 MHz state machine (i.e. a 10 ns clock), the 50 ns DRAM can perform the first read in five clock cycles, and additional reads within the same page every two clock cycles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was generally described as "5-2-2-2" timing, as bursts of four reads within a page were common.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When describing synchronous memory, timing is described by clock cycle counts separated by hyphens.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] These numbers represent *t*CL-*t*RCD-*t*RP-*t*RAS in multiples of the DRAM clock cycle time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Note that this is half of the data transfer rate when double data rate signaling is used.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] JEDEC standard PC3200 timing is 3-4-4-8 with a 200 MHz clock, while premium-priced high performance PC3200 DDR DRAM DIMM might be operated at 2-2-2-5 timing.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Minimum random access time has improved from *t*RAC = 50 ns to *t*RCD + *t*CL = 22.5 ns, and even the premium 20 ns variety is only 2.5 times faster than the asynchronous DRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] CAS latency has improved even less, from *t*CAC = 13 ns to 10 ns.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, the DDR3 memory does achieve 32 times higher bandwidth; due to internal pipelining and wide data paths, it can output two words every 1.25 ns (1600 Mword/s), while the EDO DRAM can output one word per *t*PC = 20 ns (50 Mword/s).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Each bit of data in a DRAM is stored as a positive or negative electrical charge in a capacitive structure.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The structure providing the capacitance, as well as the transistors that control access to it, is collectively referred to as a *DRAM cell*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] They are the fundamental building block in DRAM arrays.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Multiple DRAM memory cell variants exist, but the most commonly used variant in modern DRAMs is the one-transistor, one-capacitor (1T1C) cell.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The transistor is used to admit current into the capacitor during writes, and to discharge the capacitor during reads.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The access transistor is designed to maximize drive strength and minimize transistor-transistor leakage (Kenner, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor has two terminals, one of which is connected to its access transistor, and the other to either ground or VCC/2.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In modern DRAMs, the latter case is more common, since it allows faster operation.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In modern DRAMs, a voltage of +VCC/2 across the capacitor is required to store a logic one; and a voltage of −VCC/2 across the capacitor is required to store a logic zero.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The resultant charge is ${\textstyle Q=\pm {V_{CC} \over 2}\cdot C}$ , where *Q* is the charge in coulombs and *C* is the capacitance in farads.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Reading or writing a logic one requires the wordline be driven to a voltage greater than the sum of VCC and the access transistor's threshold voltage (VTH).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This voltage is called *VCC pumped* (VCCP).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The time required to discharge a capacitor thus depends on what logic value is stored in the capacitor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A capacitor containing logic one begins to discharge when the voltage at the access transistor's gate terminal is above VCCP.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] If the capacitor contains a logic zero, it begins to discharge when the gate terminal voltage is above VTH.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Up until the mid-1980s, the capacitors in DRAM cells were co-planar with the access transistor (they were constructed on the surface of the substrate), thus they were referred to as *planar* capacitors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The drive to increase both density and, to a lesser extent, performance, required denser designs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This was strongly motivated by economics, a major consideration for DRAM devices, especially commodity DRAMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The minimization of DRAM cell area can produce a denser device and lower the cost per bit of storage.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Starting in the mid-1980s, the capacitor was moved above or below the silicon substrate in order to meet these objectives.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cells featuring capacitors above the substrate are referred to as *stacked* or *folded plate* capacitors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Those with capacitors buried beneath the substrate surface are referred to as *trench* capacitors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the 2000s, manufacturers were sharply divided by the type of capacitor used in their DRAMs and the relative cost and long-term scalability of both designs have been the subject of extensive debate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The majority of DRAMs, from major manufacturers such as Hynix, Micron Technology, Samsung Electronics use the stacked capacitor structure, whereas smaller manufacturers such as Nanya Technology use the trench capacitor structure (Jacob, pp.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor in the stacked capacitor scheme is constructed above the surface of the substrate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The capacitor is constructed from an oxide-nitride-oxide (ONO) dielectric sandwiched in between two layers of polysilicon plates (the top plate is shared by all DRAM cells in an IC), and its shape can be a rectangle, a cylinder, or some other more complex shape.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] There are two basic variations of the stacked capacitor, based on its location relative to the bitline—capacitor-under-bitline (CUB) and capacitor-over-bitline (COB).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the former, the capacitor is underneath the bitline, which is usually made of metal, and the bitline has a polysilicon contact that extends downwards to connect it to the access transistor's source terminal.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In the latter, the capacitor is constructed above the bitline, which is almost always made of polysilicon, but is otherwise identical to the COB variation.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The advantage the COB variant possesses is the ease of fabricating the contact between the bitline and the access transistor's source as it is physically close to the substrate surface.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] However, this requires the active area to be laid out at a 45-degree angle when viewed from above, which makes it difficult to ensure that the capacitor contact does not touch the bitline.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] CUB cells avoid this, but suffer from difficulties in inserting contacts in between bitlines, since the size of features this close to the surface are at or near the minimum feature size of the process technology (Kenner, pp.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The trench capacitor is constructed by etching a deep hole into the silicon substrate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The substrate volume surrounding the hole is then heavily doped to produce a buried n+ plate with low resistance.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A layer of oxide-nitride-oxide dielectric is grown or deposited, and finally the hole is filled by depositing doped polysilicon, which forms the top plate of the capacitor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The top of the capacitor is connected to the access transistor's drain terminal via a polysilicon strap (Kenner, pp.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A trench capacitor's depth-to-width ratio in DRAMs of the mid-2000s can exceed 50:1 (Jacob, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Trench capacitors have numerous advantages.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the capacitor is buried in the bulk of the substrate instead of lying on its surface, the area it occupies can be minimized to what is required to connect it to the access transistor's drain terminal without decreasing the capacitor's size, and thus capacitance (Jacob, pp.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Alternatively, the capacitance can be increased by etching a deeper hole without any increase to surface area (Kenner, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Another advantage of the trench capacitor is that its structure is under the layers of metal interconnect, allowing them to be more easily made planar, which enables it to be integrated in a logic-optimized process technology, which have many levels of interconnect above the substrate.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The fact that the capacitor is under the logic means that it is constructed before the transistors are.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This allows high-temperature processes to fabricate the capacitors, which would otherwise degrade the logic transistors and their performance.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This makes trench capacitors suitable for constructing embedded DRAM (eDRAM) (Jacob, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Disadvantages of trench capacitors are difficulties in reliably constructing the capacitor's structures within deep holes and in connecting the capacitor to the access transistor's drain terminal (Kenner, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] First-generation DRAM ICs (those with capacities of 1 Kbit), such as the archetypical Intel 1103, used a three-transistor, one-capacitor (3T1C) DRAM cell with separate read and write circuitry.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The write wordline drove a write transistor which connected the capacitor to the write bitline just as in the 1T1C cell, but there was a separate read wordline and read transistor which connected an amplifier transistor to the read bitline.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] By the second generation, the drive to reduce cost by fitting the same amount of bits in a smaller area led to the almost universal adoption of the 1T1C DRAM cell, although a couple of devices with 4 and 16 Kbit capacities continued to use the 3T1C cell for performance reasons (Kenner, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] These performance advantages included, most significantly, the ability to read the state stored by the capacitor without discharging it, avoiding the need to write back what was read out (non-destructive read).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A second performance advantage relates to the 3T1C cell's separate transistors for reading and writing; the memory controller can exploit this feature to perform atomic read-modify-writes, where a value is read, modified, and then written back as a single, indivisible operation (Jacob, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The one-transistor, zero-capacitor (1T, or 1T0C) DRAM cell has been a topic of research since the late-1990s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] *1T DRAM* is a different way of constructing the basic DRAM memory cell, distinct from the classic one-transistor/one-capacitor (1T/1C) DRAM cell, which is also sometimes referred to as *1T DRAM*, particularly in comparison to the 3T and 4T DRAM which it replaced in the 1970s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In 1T DRAM cells, the bit of data is still stored in a capacitive region controlled by a transistor, but this capacitance is no longer provided by a separate capacitor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] 1T DRAM is a "capacitorless" bit cell design that stores data using the parasitic body capacitance that is inherent to silicon on insulator (SOI) transistors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Considered a nuisance in logic design, this floating body effect can be used for data storage.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This gives 1T DRAM cells the greatest density as well as allowing easier integration with high-performance logic circuits since they are constructed with the same SOI process technologies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Refreshing of cells remains necessary, but unlike with 1T1C DRAM, reads in 1T DRAM are non-destructive; the stored charge causes a detectable shift in the threshold voltage of the transistor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Performance-wise, access times are significantly better than capacitor-based DRAMs, but slightly worse than SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] There are several types of 1T DRAMs: the commercialized Z-RAM from Innovative Silicon, the TTRAM from Renesas and the A-RAM from the UGR/CNRS consortium.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cells are laid out in a regular rectangular, grid-like pattern to facilitate their control and access via wordlines and bitlines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The physical layout of the DRAM cells in an array is typically designed so that two adjacent DRAM cells in a column share a single bitline contact to reduce their area.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM cell area is given as *n*F2, where *n* is a number derived from the DRAM cell design, and *F* is the smallest feature size of a given process technology.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This scheme permits comparison of DRAM size over different process technology generations, as DRAM cell area scales at linear or near-linear rates with respect to feature size.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The typical area for modern DRAM cells varies between 6–8 F2.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The horizontal wire, the wordline, is connected to the gate terminal of every access transistor in its row.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The vertical bitline is connected to the source terminal of the transistors in its column.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The lengths of the wordlines and bitlines are limited.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The wordline length is limited by the desired performance of the array, since propagation time of the signal that must traverse the wordline is determined by the RC time constant.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bitline length is limited by its capacitance (which increases with length), which must be kept within a range for proper sensing (as DRAMs operate by sensing the charge of the capacitor released onto the bitline).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Bitline length is also limited by the amount of operating current the DRAM can draw and by how power can be dissipated, since these two characteristics are largely determined by the charging and discharging of the bitline.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Sense amplifiers are required to read the state contained in the DRAM cells.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] When the access transistor is activated, the electrical charge in the capacitor is shared with the bitline.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The bitline's capacitance is much greater than that of the capacitor (approximately ten times).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Thus, the change in bitline voltage is minute.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Sense amplifiers are required to resolve the voltage differential into the levels specified by the logic signaling system.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Modern DRAMs use differential sense amplifiers, and are accompanied by requirements as to how the DRAM arrays are constructed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Differential sense amplifiers work by driving their outputs to opposing extremes based on the relative voltages on pairs of bitlines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The sense amplifiers function effectively and efficiently only if the capacitance and voltages of these bitline pairs are closely matched.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Besides ensuring that the lengths of the bitlines and the number of DRAM cells attached to them are equal, two basic architectures to array design have emerged to provide for the requirements of the sense amplifiers: open and folded bitline arrays.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first generation (1 Kbit) DRAM ICs, up until the 64 Kbit generation (and some 256 Kbit generation devices) had open bitline array architectures.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In these architectures, the bitlines are divided into multiple segments, and the differential sense amplifiers are placed in between bitline segments.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Because the sense amplifiers are placed between bitline segments, to route their outputs outside the array, an additional layer of interconnect placed above those used to construct the wordlines and bitlines is required.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The DRAM cells that are on the edges of the array do not have adjacent segments.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since the differential sense amplifiers require identical capacitance and bitline lengths from both segments, dummy bitline segments are provided.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The advantage of the open bitline array is a smaller array area, although this advantage is slightly diminished by the dummy bitline segments.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The disadvantage that caused the near disappearance of this architecture is the inherent vulnerability to noise, which affects the effectiveness of the differential sense amplifiers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Since each bitline segment does not have any spatial relationship to the other, it is likely that noise would affect only one of the two bitline segments.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded bitline array architecture routes bitlines in pairs throughout the array.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The close proximity of the paired bitlines provide superior common-mode noise rejection characteristics over open bitline arrays.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded bitline array architecture began appearing in DRAM ICs during the mid-1980s, beginning with the 256 Kbit generation.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This architecture is favored in modern DRAM ICs for its superior noise immunity.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This architecture is referred to as *folded* because it takes its basis from the open array architecture from the perspective of the circuit schematic.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The folded array architecture appears to remove DRAM cells in alternate pairs (because two DRAM cells share a single bitline contact) from a column, then move the DRAM cells from an adjacent column into the voids.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The location where the bitline twists occupies additional area.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] To minimize area overhead, engineers select the simplest and most area-minimal twisting scheme that is able to reduce noise under the specified limit.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As process technology improves to reduce minimum feature sizes, the signal to noise problem worsens, since coupling between adjacent metal wires is inversely proportional to their pitch.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The array folding and bitline twisting schemes that are used must increase in complexity in order to maintain sufficient noise reduction.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Schemes that have desirable noise immunity characteristics for a minimal impact in area is the topic of current research (Kenner, p.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Advances in process technology could result in open bitline array architectures being favored if it is able to offer better long-term area efficiencies; since folded array architectures require increasingly complex folding schemes to match any advance in process technology.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The relationship between process technology, array architecture, and area efficiency is an active area of research.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The first DRAM integrated circuits did not have any redundancy.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] An integrated circuit with a defective DRAM cell would be discarded.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Beginning with the 64 Kbit generation, DRAM arrays have included spare rows and columns to improve yields.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Spare rows and columns provide tolerance of minor fabrication defects which have caused a small number of rows or columns to be inoperable.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The defective rows and columns are physically disconnected from the rest of the array by triggering a programmable fuse or by cutting the wire by a laser.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The spare rows or columns are substituted in by remapping logic in the row and column decoders (Jacob, pp.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Electrical or magnetic interference inside a computer system can cause a single bit of DRAM to spontaneously flip to the opposite state.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The majority of one-off ("soft") errors in DRAM chips occur as a result of background radiation, chiefly neutrons from cosmic ray secondaries, which may change the contents of one or more memory cells or interfere with the circuitry used to read/write them.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The problem can be mitigated by using redundant memory bits and additional circuitry that use these bits to detect and correct soft errors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In most cases, the detection and correction are performed by the memory controller; sometimes, the required logic is transparently implemented within DRAM chips or modules, enabling the ECC memory functionality for otherwise ECC-incapable systems.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The extra memory bits are used to record parity and to enable missing data to be reconstructed by error-correcting code (ECC).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Parity allows the detection of all single-bit errors (actually, any odd number of wrong bits).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The most common error-correcting code, a SECDED Hamming code, allows a single-bit error to be corrected and, in the usual configuration, with an extra parity bit, double-bit errors to be detected.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Recent studies give widely varying error rates with over seven orders of magnitude difference, ranging from 10−10−10−17 error/bit·h, roughly one bit error, per hour, per gigabyte of memory to one bit error, per century, per gigabyte of memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] A 2010 study at the University of Rochester also gave evidence that a substantial fraction of memory errors are intermittent hard errors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Although dynamic memory is only specified and *guaranteed* to retain its contents when supplied with power and refreshed every short period of time (often 64 ms), the memory cell capacitors often retain their values for significantly longer time, particularly at low temperatures.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Under some conditions most of the data in DRAM can be recovered even if it has not been refreshed for several minutes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This property can be used to circumvent security and recover data stored in the main memory that is assumed to be destroyed at power-down.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The computer could be quickly rebooted, and the contents of the main memory read out; or by removing a computer's memory modules, cooling them to prolong data remanence, then transferring them to a different computer to be read out.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Such an attack was demonstrated to circumvent popular disk encryption systems, such as the open source TrueCrypt, Microsoft's BitLocker Drive Encryption, and Apple's FileVault.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] This type of attack against a computer is often called a cold boot attack.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Dynamic memory, by definition, requires periodic refresh.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Furthermore, reading dynamic memory is a destructive operation, requiring a recharge of the storage cells in the row that has been read.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] If these processes are imperfect, a read operation can cause soft errors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] In particular, there is a risk that some charge can leak between nearby cells, causing the refresh or read of one row to cause a *disturbance error* in an adjacent or even nearby row.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The awareness of disturbance errors dates back to the first commercially available DRAM in the early 1970s (the Intel 1103).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Despite the mitigation techniques employed by manufacturers, commercial researchers proved in a 2014 analysis that commercially available DDR3 DRAM chips manufactured in 2012 and 2013 are susceptible to disturbance errors.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The associated side effect that led to observed bit flips has been dubbed *row hammer*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Dynamic RAM ICs can be packaged in molded epoxy cases, with an internal lead frame for interconnections between the silicon die and the package leads.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] The original IBM PC design used ICs, including those for DRAM, packaged in dual in-line packages (DIP), soldered directly to the main board or mounted in sockets.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] As memory density skyrocketed, the DIP package was no longer practical.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] For convenience in handling, several dynamic RAM integrated circuits may be mounted on a single memory module, allowing installation of 16-bit, 32-bit or 64-bit wide memory in a single unit, without the requirement for the installer to insert multiple individual integrated circuits.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Memory modules may include additional devices for parity checking or error correction.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Over the evolution of desktop computers, several standardized types of memory module have been developed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Laptop computers, game consoles, and specialized devices may have their own formats of memory modules not interchangeable with standard desktop parts for packaging or proprietary reasons.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] DRAM that is integrated into an integrated circuit designed in a logic-optimized process (such as an application-specific integrated circuit, microprocessor, or an entire system on a chip) is called *embedded DRAM* (eDRAM).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p01] Embedded DRAM requires DRAM cell designs that can be fabricated without preventing the fabrication of fast-switching transistors used in high-performance logic, and modification of the basic logic-optimized process technology to accommodate the process steps required to build DRAM cell structures.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Since the fundamental DRAM cell and array has maintained the same basic structure for many years, the types of DRAM are mainly distinguished by the many different interfaces for communicating with DRAM chips.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The original DRAM, now known by the retronym *asynchronous DRAM* was the first type of DRAM in use.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] From its origins in the late 1960s, it was commonplace in computing up until around 1997, when it was mostly replaced by *synchronous DRAM*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In the present day, manufacture of asynchronous RAM is relatively rare.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An asynchronous DRAM chip has power connections, some number of address inputs (typically 12), and a few (typically one or four) bidirectional data lines.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This interface provides direct control of internal timing: when RAS is driven low, a CAS cycle must not be attempted until the sense amplifiers have sensed the memory state, and RAS must not be returned high until the storage cells have been refreshed.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] When RAS is driven high, it must be held high long enough for precharging to complete.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Although the DRAM is asynchronous, the signals are typically generated by a clocked memory controller, which limits their timing to multiples of the controller's clock cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Classic asynchronous DRAM is refreshed by opening each row in turn.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The refresh cycles are distributed across the entire refresh interval in such a way that all rows are refreshed within the required interval.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] At the end of the required amount of time, RAS must return high.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This can be done by supplying a row address and pulsing RAS low; it is not necessary to perform any CAS cycles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An external counter is needed to iterate over the row addresses in turn.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In some designs, the CPU handled RAM refresh.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The Zilog Z80 is perhaps the best known example, as it has an internal row counter R which supplies the address for a special refresh cycle generated after each instruction fetch.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In other systems, especially home computers, refresh was handled by the video circuitry as a side effect of its periodic scan of the frame buffer.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] For convenience, the counter was quickly incorporated into the DRAM chips themselves.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] If the CAS line is driven low before RAS (normally an illegal operation), then the DRAM ignores the address inputs and uses an internal counter to select the row to open.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This is known as CAS-before-RAS (CBR) refresh.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This became the standard form of refresh for asynchronous DRAM, and is the only form generally used with SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Given support of CAS-before-RAS refresh, it is possible to deassert RAS while holding CAS low to maintain data output.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] If RAS is then asserted again, this performs a CBR refresh cycle while the DRAM outputs remain valid.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Because data output is not interrupted, this is known as *hidden refresh*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Hidden refresh is no faster than a normal read followed by a normal refresh, but does maintain the data output valid during the refresh cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Page mode DRAM was in turn later improved with a small modification which further reduced latency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DRAMs with this improvement are called **fast page mode DRAMs** (**FPM DRAMs**).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In page mode DRAM, the chip does not capture the column address until CAS is asserted, so column access time (until data out was valid) begins when CAS is asserted.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] In FPM DRAM, the column address can be supplied while CAS is still deasserted, and the main column access time (*t*AA) begins as soon as the address is stable.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The CAS signal is only needed to enable the output (the data out pins were held at high-Z while CAS was deasserted), so time from CAS assertion to data valid (*t*CAC) is greatly reduced.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Fast page mode DRAM was introduced in 1986 and was used with the Intel 80486.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Extended data out DRAM (EDO DRAM) was invented and patented in the 1990s by Micron Technology who then licensed technology to many other memory manufacturers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] EDO RAM, sometimes referred to as *hyper page mode* enabled DRAM, is similar to fast page mode DRAM with the additional feature that a new access cycle can be started while keeping the data output of the previous cycle active.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This can be used to overlap operations a certain amount (pipelining) and improve performance somewhat.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is up to 30% faster than FPM DRAM which it began to replace in 1995 when Intel introduced the 430FX chipset with EDO DRAM support.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Regardless of the performance gains, FPM and EDO SIMMs can be used interchangeably in many (but not all) applications.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] To be precise, EDO DRAM begins data output on the falling edge of CAS but does not disable the output when CAS rises again.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Instead, it holds the current output valid (thus extending the data output time) even as the DRAM begins decoding a new column address, until either a new column's data is selected by another CAS falling edge, or the output is switched off by the rising edge of RAS.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] EDO's capabilities were able to partially compensate for the performance lost due to the lack of an L2 cache in low-cost, commodity PCs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] More expensive notebooks also often lacked an L2 cache due to size and power limitations, and benefitted similarly.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Even for systems *with* an L2 cache, the availability of EDO memory improved the average memory latency seen by applications over earlier FPM implementations.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Single-cycle EDO DRAM became very popular on video cards toward the end of the 1990s.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It was very low cost, yet nearly as efficient for performance as the far more costly VRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An evolution of EDO DRAM, burst EDO DRAM (BEDO DRAM), could process four memory addresses in one burst, for a maximum of 5-1-1-1, saving an additional three clocks over optimally designed EDO memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It was done by adding an address counter on the chip to keep track of the next address.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] BEDO also added a pipeline stage allowing page-access cycle to be divided into two parts.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] During a memory-read operation, the first part accessed the data from the memory array to the output stage (second latch).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The second part drove the data bus from this latch at the appropriate logic level.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Since the data is already in the output buffer, quicker access time is achieved (up to 50% for large blocks of data) than with traditional EDO.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Although BEDO DRAM showed additional optimization over EDO, by the time it was available the market had made a significant investment towards synchronous DRAM, or SDRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Even though BEDO RAM was superior to SDRAM in some ways, the latter technology quickly displaced BEDO.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Synchronous dynamic RAM (SDRAM) significantly revises the asynchronous memory interface, adding a clock (and a clock enable) line.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] All other signals are received on the rising edge of the clock.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The OE line's function is extended to a per-byte DQM signal, which controls data input (writes) in addition to data output (reads).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This allows DRAM chips to be wider than 8 bits while still supporting byte-granularity writes.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Many timing parameters remain under the control of the DRAM controller.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] For example, a minimum time must elapse between a row being activated and a read or write command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] One important parameter must be programmed into the SDRAM chip itself, namely the CAS latency.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] This is the number of clock cycles allowed for internal operations between a read command and the first data word appearing on the data bus.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The *Load mode register* command is used to transfer this value to the SDRAM chip.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Other configurable parameters include the length of read and write bursts, i.e. the number of words transferred per read or write command.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The most significant change, and the primary reason that SDRAM has supplanted asynchronous RAM, is the support for multiple internal banks inside the DRAM chip.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Using a few bits of *bank address* that accompany each command, a second bank can be activated and begin reading data *while a read from the first bank is in progress*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] By alternating banks, a single SDRAM device can keep the data bus continuously busy, in a way that asynchronous DRAM cannot.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Single data rate SDRAM (SDR SDRAM or SDR) is the original generation of SDRAM; it made a single transfer of data per clock cycle.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Double data rate SDRAM (DDR SDRAM or DDR) was a later development of SDRAM, used in PC memory beginning in 2000.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Subsequent specifications are numbered sequentially (*DDR2*, *DDR3*, etc.).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DDR SDRAM internally performs double-width accesses at the clock rate, and uses a double data rate interface to transfer one half on each clock edge.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] DDR2 and DDR3 increased this factor to 4× and 8×, respectively, delivering 4-word and 8-word bursts over 2 and 4 clock cycles, respectively.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] The internal access rate is mostly unchanged (200 million per second for DDR-400, DDR2-800 and DDR3-1600 memory), but each access transfers more data.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Reduced Latency DRAM (RLDRAM) is a high performance double data rate (DDR) SDRAM that combines fast, random access with high bandwidth, mainly intended for networking and caching applications.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Graphics RAMs are asynchronous and synchronous DRAMs designed for graphics-related tasks such as texture memory and framebuffers, found on video cards.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Video DRAM (VRAM) is a dual-ported variant of DRAM that was once commonly used to store the frame buffer in some graphics adapters.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Window DRAM (WRAM) is a variant of VRAM that was once used in graphics adapters such as the Matrox Millennium and ATI 3D Rage Pro.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] WRAM was designed to perform better and cost less than VRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] WRAM offered up to 25% greater bandwidth than VRAM and accelerated commonly used graphical operations such as text drawing and block fills.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Multibank DRAM (MDRAM) is a type of specialized DRAM developed by MoSys.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is constructed from small memory banks of 256 kB, which are operated in an interleaved fashion, providing bandwidths suitable for graphics cards at a lower cost to memories such as SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] MDRAM also allows operations to two banks in a single clock cycle, permitting multiple concurrent accesses to occur if the accesses were independent.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] MDRAM was primarily used in graphic cards, such as those featuring the Tseng Labs ET6x00 chipsets.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Boards based upon this chipset often had the unusual capacity of 2.25 MB because of MDRAM's ability to be implemented more easily with such capacities.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] A graphics card with 2.25 MB of MDRAM had enough memory to provide 24-bit color at a resolution of 1024 × 768—a very popular setting at the time.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Synchronous graphics RAM (SGRAM) is a specialized form of SDRAM for graphics adapters.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It adds functions such as bit masking (writing to a specified bit plane without affecting the others) and block write (filling a block of memory with a single color).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Unlike VRAM and WRAM, SGRAM is single-ported.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] However, it can open two memory pages at once, which simulates the dual-port nature of other video RAM technologies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Graphics double data rate SDRAM is a type of specialized DDR SDRAM designed to be used as the main memory of graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] GDDR SDRAM is distinct from commodity types of DDR SDRAM such as DDR3, although they share some core technologies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Their primary characteristics are higher clock frequencies for both the DRAM core and I/O interface, which provides greater memory bandwidth for GPUs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] As of 2025, there are eight successive generations of GDDR: GDDR2, GDDR3, GDDR4, GDDR5, GDDR5X, GDDR6, GDDR6X and GDDR7.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Pseudostatic RAM (PSRAM or PSDRAM) is dynamic RAM with built-in refresh and address-control circuitry to make it behave similarly to static RAM (SRAM).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It combines the high density of DRAM with the ease of use of true SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] PSRAM was used in the Apple iPhone 3G and other embedded systems such as XFlar Platform.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Some DRAM components have a *self-refresh mode*.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] While this involves much of the same logic that is needed for pseudo-static operation, this mode is often equivalent to a standby mode.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is provided primarily to allow a system to suspend operation of its DRAM controller to save power without losing data stored in DRAM, rather than to allow operation without a separate DRAM controller as is in the case of mentioned PSRAMs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] An embedded variant of PSRAM was sold by MoSys under the name 1T-SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is a set of small DRAM banks with an SRAM cache in front to make it behave much like a true SRAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] It is used in Nintendo GameCube and Wii video game consoles.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/dynamic-random-access-memory-p02] Cypress Semiconductor's HyperRAM is a type of PSRAM supporting a JEDEC-compliant 8-pin HyperBus or Octal xSPI interface.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] A **memory controller**, also known as **memory chip controller** (**MCC**) or a **memory controller unit** (**MCU**), is a digital circuit that manages the flow of data going to and from a computer's main memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] When a memory controller is integrated into another chip, such as an integral part of a microprocessor, it is usually called an **integrated memory controller** (**IMC**).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Memory controllers contain the logic necessary to read and write to dynamic random-access memory (DRAM), and to provide the critical memory refresh and other functions.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Some memory controllers, such as the one integrated into PowerQUICC II processors, include error detection and correction hardware.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Many modern processors are also integrated memory management unit (MMU), which in many operating systems implements virtual addressing.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] On early x86-32 processors, the MMU is integrated in the CPU, but the memory controller is usually part of northbridge.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Older Intel and PowerPC-based computers have memory controller chips that are separate from the main processor.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Often these are integrated into the northbridge of the computer, also sometimes called a memory controller hub.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Most modern desktop or workstation microprocessors use an **integrated memory controller** (**IMC**), including microprocessors from Intel, AMD, and those built around the ARM architecture.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Prior to K8 (circa 2003), AMD microprocessors had a memory controller implemented on their motherboard's northbridge.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] In K8 and later, AMD employed an integrated memory controller.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Likewise, until Nehalem (circa 2008), Intel microprocessors used memory controllers implemented on the motherboard's northbridge.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Nehalem and later switched to an integrated memory controller.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Other examples of microprocessor architectures that use *integrated memory controllers* include NVIDIA's Fermi, IBM's POWER5, and Sun Microsystems's UltraSPARC T1.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] While an integrated memory controller has the potential to increase the system's performance, such as by reducing memory latency, it locks the microprocessor to a specific type (or types) of memory, forcing a redesign in order to support newer memory technologies.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] When DDR2 SDRAM was introduced, AMD released new Athlon 64 CPUs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] These new models, with a DDR2 controller, use a different physical socket (known as Socket 754), so that they will only fit in motherboards designed for the new type of RAM.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] When the memory controller is not on-die, the same CPU may be installed on a new motherboard, with an updated northbridge to use newer memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Some microprocessors in the 1990s, such as the DEC Alpha 21066 and HP PA-7300LC, had integrated memory controllers; however, rather than for performance gains, this was implemented to reduce the cost of systems by eliminating the need for an external memory controller.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Some CPUs are designed to have their memory controllers as dedicated external components that are not part of the chipset.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] An example is IBM POWER8, which uses external Centaur chips that are mounted onto DIMM modules and act as memory buffers, L4 cache chips, and as the actual memory controllers.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] The first version of the Centaur chip used DDR3 memory but an updated version was later released which can use DDR4.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] A few experimental memory controllers contain a second level of address translation, in addition to the first level of address translation performed by the CPU's memory management unit to improve cache and bus performance.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Memory controllers integrated into certain Intel Core processors provide **memory scrambling** as a feature that turns user data written to the main memory into pseudo-random patterns.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Memory scrambling has the potential to prevent forensic and reverse-engineering analysis based on DRAM data remanence by effectively rendering various types of cold boot attacks ineffective.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] In current practice, this has not been achieved; memory scrambling has only been designed to address DRAM-related electrical problems.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] The late 2010s memory scrambling standards do address security issues and are not cryptographically secure or open to public revision or analysis.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] ASUS and Intel have their separate memory scrambling standards.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] ASUS motherboards have allowed the user to choose which memory scrambling standard to use (ASUS or Intel) or whether to turn the feature off entirely.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Single data rate (SDR) memory controllers drive SDR SDRAM, where data is transferred once per clock.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] They are far simpler than double data rate memory controllers, but have been phased out due to their significantly reduced transfer speeds compared to DDR memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Double data rate (DDR) memory controllers are used to drive DDR SDRAM, where data is transferred on both rising and falling edges of the system's memory clock.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] DDR memory controllers are significantly more complicated when compared to single data rate controllers, but they allow for twice the data to be transferred without increasing the memory's clock rate or bus width.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Multichannel memory controllers are memory controllers where the DRAM devices are separated onto multiple buses to allow the memory controller(s) to access them in parallel.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] This increases the theoretical amount of bandwidth of the bus by a factor of the number of channels.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] While a channel for every DRAM would be the ideal solution, adding more channels increases complexity and cost.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Fully buffered memory systems place a memory buffer device on every memory module (called an FB-DIMM when fully buffered RAM is used), which unlike traditional memory controller devices, uses a serial data link to the memory controller instead of the parallel link used in previous RAM designs.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] This decreases the number of wires necessary to place the memory devices on a motherboard (allowing for a smaller number of layers to be used, meaning more memory devices can be placed on a single board), at the expense of increasing latency (the time necessary to access a memory location).
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] This increase is due to the time required to convert the parallel information read from the DRAM cell to the serial format used by the FB-DIMM controller, and back to a parallel form in the memory controller on the motherboard.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Error correction code (ECC) memory controllers drive ECC memory.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] ECC corrects common errors encountered by RAM and significantly reduces data loss and increases stability.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] It also slightly increases the RAM's bus width (typically from 64 to 72 bytes) to consolidate for this extra code.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] It is rarely needed in personal computing, but is commonly found in servers and workstations where increased stability and data integrity are important.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Many flash memory devices, such as USB flash drives and solid-state drives, include a flash memory controller.
[src:ddr-memory-interface/memory-controller] Flash memory is inherently slower to access than RAM and often becomes unusable after a few million write cycles, which generally makes it unsuitable for RAM applications.
